In [[High performance liquid chromatography|liquid chromatography]], '''isocratic flow''' describes a [[mobile phase]] of constant composition.
{{Chemistry-stub}}
In contrast to this is the so called "gradient elution", which is a separation where the mobile phase changes its composition during a separation process. One example is a gradient in 20 min starting from 10% MeOH and ending up with 30%MeOH. Such a gradient can be increasing or decreasing.